		<div class="post" id="post-3590744">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,3590744)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-3590744">
																		Commentary
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/decibelles" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2005044); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2005044&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251709" alt="Decibelles" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2005044)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/decibelles" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2005044); return false;" >Decibelles</a></span> <span class="odate time_1505262506 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">13 Sep 2017 00:28</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3590744">
									

<p>This fits well on my author page; I dunno if I'd make a thread on the forums about it.</p>
<p>There's three articles I've written as of this moment that I'm super proud of, and consider my best writing on this site and among my best writing ever. They are, as follows and in order: <a href="/scp-3090">SCP-3090</a>, <a href="/i-forget-myself-in-this-wondrous-night">I Forget Myself in This Wondrous Night</a>, and <a href="/scp-2246">SCP-2246</a>.</p>
<h2><span>SCP-3090</span></h2>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Show.</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Hide.</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>This was co-written with <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/th4nkyoub3n" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3079214); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3079214&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1505262505" alt="th4nkyoub3n" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3079214)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/th4nkyoub3n" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3079214); return false;">th4nkyoub3n</a></span>, and originally authored by him. So, keep that in mind.</p>
<p>This is my best writing on the site simply because it expresses a lot of what I want to tell about the Foundation in a simple, streamlined way. The interactions between humanoid anomaly and researcher, the line of treating the anomaly like an object versus a person, mental health, video games, being gay, being trans, etc.. I could (and absolutely can) write an entire article on each of these subjects alone, but figured each of them can make an interesting part of a whole story in one article. Mental health is a big thing for me, something I'm both hurt by and fascinated by. How does one react under certain situations? The whole mantra of showing and not telling applies here, but I wanted to tell a bit to get it across. Heather escapes in video games in a sort of real literal sense, while alive and while an anomaly. It's a good way to escape anxiety and depression, and I feel much the same way.</p>
<p>Plus, any article people will cite it as an example of the SCP Wiki failing, being shitty as a whole merely by existing, being too SJW, or act like immature babies over is a real successful one. It weeds out the people who read fiction for the wrong reasons and don't want to look closer into. Plus, I feel like I've succeeded in creating a character I genuinely love with this. I've never written a character before that I was really into, either merely liking or writing only in service to the story. So, yeah, this is my favorite thing of mine and maybe the best thing I've written.</p>
<p>There's also a contingent of people who hate this solely because it has any association with Gamers Against Weed, to which I say, come the fuck on. The main thrust and core of this article only uses that as a launchpad to run with something else altogether. Anyone who read this, saw the GoI, and downvoted never had an interest in connecting to or reading or analyzing this article on any sort of scale IMO. It'd almost be entirely the same without the GAW connection. The only major things I'd lose are the sense of community and the theme of minorities carving their way out in the world of anomalous happenings, both of which I think provide necessary background to make this more than &quot;cute girl with TV for head does stuff to video games&quot;. It adds a layer to this that makes it more human. I will admit that not every reader is gonna be connected to someone who's trans and gay and is a girl, and who has a defensive guard surrounding that to dictate their actions. But also, nearly everything I write on this site now is filled with LGBT themes, so it's just par for the course if you're reading my stuff.</p>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Hide.</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<h2><span>I Forget Myself in This Wondrous Night</span></h2>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Show.</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Hide.</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>This is obstinately a tale about <a href="/scp-1467">SCP-1467</a>. And it wholly is, but it's a lot more.</p>
<p>I published this May 7, 2015. In truth, it was being written for years. This is where my fascination with writing about mental health is at its most obvious. The reason why I connect and love 1467 so much is because it's real easy to read it as a metaphor for&#8230; a lot. It's up to reader interpretation, I suppose. I'll spare you how I view it; what's important is the writing. I wrote this a week or two after I broke up with my girlfriend in April. The first part of the tale was all I wrote, and it was done in a hurry one night. <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/thedeadlymoose" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(732274); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=732274&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1505262505" alt="thedeadlymoose" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=732274)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/thedeadlymoose" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(732274); return false;">thedeadlymoose</a></span>, <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/djkaktus" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1888434); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1888434&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1505262505" alt="djkaktus" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1888434)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/djkaktus" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1888434); return false;">djkaktus</a></span>, <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/communism-will-win" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(617958); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=617958&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1505262505" alt="Communism will win" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=617958)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/communism-will-win" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(617958); return false;">Communism will win</a></span>, and <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/twistedgears" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1735681); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1735681&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1505262505" alt="TwistedGears" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1735681)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/twistedgears" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1735681); return false;">TwistedGears</a></span> all liked it and encouraged me to continue, so I did. Over the course of three nights (one of those being an all-nighter), I wrote and wrote and wrote and edited this like you could not believe. It shows; only someone who's mad would write an article that essentially treats its audience like their therapist.</p>
<p>I love prose that's off-kilter, purple and normal, grounded in reality but ever so fanciful. It immediately represents a viewpoint that comes from two different places at once, even if it shares a common origin (in this case, the third-person view of Mr. Smith), which I think helps establish the mood I'm going for. It's, in essence, a story about being lost and losing yourself. It's a feeling most can relate to, but especially people with mental illness like myself, so I had to make it as universal as I could. And I did I think. I pulled it off real well.</p>
<p>The only reason why this doesn't surpass 3090 for me is because Smith isn't an original character. I adapted a character with gaps in his story and then constructed a personal narrative around. This is the challenge inherent to this site in writing tales about characters in other tales or SCPs. This is a story, by the way, that could have only been written and published in a certain period of my life. It was either then or never. I'll never write a story like this again, nor would I want to. It's the manifestation of emotions and expressions I only could have gotten out then. But if I were totally normal and still happily dating, would it be worth not having this story? Yes, it would.</p>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Hide.</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<h2><span>SCP-2246</span></h2>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Show.</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Hide.</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>I always wanted to write about writer's block; my first idea was a -J that was a block that made it hard to write (hah). I soon threw that away. This was during the period in which I didn't think I wanted to write for the site anymore and my main muse of inspiration (TwistedGears) rapidly drifted away. Up to the point of me writing this article, I had not posted for almost seven months, and hadn't even attempted to write for five straight months.</p>
<p>The idea that this spun off of was &quot;what if the process of writing itself could be an SCP?&quot; and this eventually turned into what it is here. Some people have read into this thinking it was metacommentary on writing; they can choose to take that as their own interpretation, but it wasn't what I intended. I wanted to highlight my very real struggle of how people view my work and how I am perceived on a day-to-day basis, along with the level of scrutiny writing gets. This will sound weird, but I wanted to convey this in a very direct and simplistic way to the majority of readers by making Phoenix very much autistic and give them a lot of the traits that I have. Understanding the world and viewing it through the lens of autism, of course, is not direct or simple, but it's the best way to understand how I feel and how Phoenix feels, and thus convey it easier than being ultra subtle with my showing.</p>
<p>This has been criticized for being too wanky or pretentious. Which is funny, because this skip is everything but wanky and pretentious. The reason why I never show excerpts from Phoenix's writing is because I don't want to dip this article into the field of pretension or lose sight of the main goal, and I wanted it to be as clear and direct as I possibly could.</p>
<p>As for the meaning behind the title, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=50HSR_bVfAM">You Set the Scene</a>, well, <a href="https://genius.com/Love-you-set-the-scene-lyrics">basically everything from Verse 2 and on</a>.</p>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Hide.</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>I hope this helps bring some new insight to the articles. If you're a fan of these articles or my work, I encourage you to reread these with this knowledge in mind and to try and consider authorial intent and their process of writing in reading other articles. Thank you.</p>

							</div>

								
					
